First Hypothesis Test;

For data available in the years before the covid pandemic, is the average acute

bed occupancy in winter (Q4 + Q1) significantly greater than in summer (Q2 + Q3)?

Focus on pre-covid timeline (2016 - 2019) to set a benchmark;

seasonal_precovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy <- total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  separate(quarter, into = c("year", "quarter"), sep = "Q") %>% 
  mutate(season = if_else(quarter == 1 | quarter == 4, "winter", "summer"), 
         .after = "quarter") %>% 
  filter(year <= 2019) 

seasonal_precovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = season, y = mean_total_acute_occupancy) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "#433685", alpha = 0.5) +
  stat_boxplot(geom = "errorbar", width = 0.25) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "% Overall Acute Bed Occupancy by Season, Scotland, Q3|2016 - Q4|2019",
       x = "\nSeason",
       y = "% Bed Occupancy") +
  theme(title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Set α = 0.05.

Null hypothesis H0: Mean acute bed occupancy between 2016 - 2019 is the same in the summer months as in the winter months; \[ H_0: μ_{winter2016 - 2019} − μ_{summer2016 - 2019} = 0 \]

Alternative hypothesis H1: Mean acute bed occupancy between 2016 - 2019 is greater in winter than in summer; \[ H_1: μ_{winter2016 - 2019} − μ_{summer2016 - 2019} > 0 \]

Generation of null distribution: under H0, where xs and ys are independent, it wouldn’t matter how you split the observations into group 1 or group 2, there wouldn’t be a statistically significant difference between the means or proportions of the 2 groups. So randomly shuffle (permute) the labels (the ys) of the observations to randomly assign the observations into groups 1 and 2. We then calculate the difference in sample means or proportions for the two groups. This is repeated many times (e.g. 10,000) to create the null distribution.

observed_stat <- seasonal_precovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  specify(mean_total_acute_occupancy ~ season) %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("winter", "summer"))

observed_stat

Generate and visualise the null distribution with observed_stat overlaid;

null_distribution <- seasonal_precovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  specify(mean_total_acute_occupancy ~ season) %>% 
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 10000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("winter", "summer"))
null_distribution %>% 
  visualise() +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

Calculate the p-value;

p_value <- null_distribution %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

p_value

Conclusion of first hypothesis test;

The p-value for this test is below α = 0.05. In this case we reject H0 and conclude that there is enough evidence in our data to suggest that the average acute bed occupancy in winter is statistically significantly greater than in summer.

Second Hypothesis Test;

For data available in the years during the covid pandemic, is the average acute

bed occupancy in winter (Q4 + Q1) significantly greater than in summer (Q2 + Q3)?

Focus on covid-affected timeline (2020 - 2021);

seasonal_postcovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy <- total_avg_acute_occupancy %>%

It looks like there’s a really low value in the summer distribution; is this an outlier > 3σ from the mean? Check the z-score;

seasonal_postcovid_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  filter(season == "summer") %>% 
  mutate(z_occupancy = scale(mean_total_acute_occupancy))

So within the context of 2020-2021 seasonal data there are no data points more than 3σ from the mean. The closest point to this is the data point for 2020 Q2, at -1.44σ.

Set α = 0.05.

Null hypothesis H0: Mean acute bed occupancy between 2020 - 2021 is the same in the summer months as in the winter months; \[ H_0: μ_{winter2020 - 2021} − μ_{summer2020 - 2021} = 0 \]

Alternative hypothesis H1: Mean acute bed occupancy between 2020 - 2021 is greater in winter than in summer; \[ H_1: μ_{winter2020 - 2021} − μ_{summer2020 - 2021} > 0 \]

Generation of null distribution: under H0, where xs and ys are independent, it wouldn’t matter how you split the observations into group 1 or group 2, there wouldn’t be a statistically significant difference between the means or proportions of the 2 groups. So randomly shuffle (permute) the labels (the ys) of the observations to randomly assign the observations into groups 1 and 2. We then calculate the difference in sample means or proportions for the two groups. This is repeated many times (e.g. 10,000) to create the null distribution.

Third Hypothesis Test;

For all data available in before and during the covid pandemic, is the average acute

bed occupancy in winter (Q4 + Q1) significantly greater than in summer (Q2 + Q3)?

Use all data (2016 - 2021);

seasonal_total_avg_acute_occupancy <- total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  separate(quarter, into = c("year", "quarter"), sep = "Q") %>% 
  mutate(season = if_else(quarter == 1 | quarter == 4, "winter", "summer"), 
         .after = "quarter")

seasonal_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = season, y = mean_total_acute_occupancy) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "#433685", alpha = 0.5) +
  stat_boxplot(geom = "errorbar", width = 0.25) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "% Overall Acute Bed Occupancy by Season, Scotland, Q3|2016 - Q3|2021",
       x = "\nSeason",
       y = "% Bed Occupancy") +
  theme(title = element_text(face = "bold"))

Set α = 0.05.

Null hypothesis H0: Average acute bed occupancy between 2016 - 2021 is the same in the summer months as in the winter months; \[ H_0: μ_{winter2016 - 2021} − μ_{summer2016 - 2021} = 0 \]

Alternative hypothesis H1: Average acute bed occupancy between 2016 - 2021 is greater in winter than in summer; \[ H_1: μ_{winter2016 - 2021} − μ_{summer2016 - 2021} > 0 \]

Generation of null distribution: under H0, where xs and ys are independent, it wouldn’t matter how you split the observations into group 1 or group 2, there wouldn’t be a statistically significant difference between the means or proportions of the 2 groups. So randomly shuffle (permute) the labels (the ys) of the observations to randomly assign the observations into groups 1 and 2. We then calculate the difference in sample means or proportions for the two groups. This is repeated many times (e.g. 10,000) to create the null distribution.

observed_stat <- seasonal_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  specify(mean_total_acute_occupancy ~ season) %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("winter", "summer"))

observed_stat

Generate and visualise the null distribution with observed_stat overlaid;

null_distribution <- seasonal_total_avg_acute_occupancy %>% 
  specify(mean_total_acute_occupancy ~ season) %>% 
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 50000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("winter", "summer"))
null_distribution %>% 
  visualise() +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

Calculate the p-value;

p_value <- null_distribution %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

p_value

This is larger than our alpha level of 0.05 which means that we cannot reject H0. That means we cannot say from the evidence in this dataset that the difference in average bed occupancy across the whole dataset including pre- and post-covid onset is varying on a seasonal basis. This may change if we extended our timeline to include earlier data.
